Red Wine Quality Exploratory Data Analysis by Saul Geller

## Number of missing values: 0
## Number of null values: 0

The dataframe contains around 1600 entries for various red wines. Each entry contains a quality rating score between 0 and 10, and 11 chemical properties, all with numerical values. There are no missing or NULL values so no data cleaning is necessary at this point. I did decide to change the column named “sulphates” to “sulfates” just to be more consistent with the spelling, and I also shortened some column names.

Looking at the summary of the columns in the dataframe, nothing crazy stands out. There do seem to be some relatively high maximum values compared to the minimum and median values, indicating some potential outliers. The pH values also look surprisingly acidic, though I don’t know much about wine pH going into this project.

I also want to make a note of the units of the data, given by the data info text document provided by the authors of the dataset. Most of these columns are given in some form of density unit; the only exceptions being pH, percent alcohol, and the quality score. The unit g/dm^3, which applies to fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, and sulphates, means grams per decimeter cubed. A decimeter cubed is also 1 liter, so more simply this unit is grams per liter.

The free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide are given in mg/dm^3 which is just milligrams per liter, and the overall density of the wine is given in g/cm^3 which is also grams per milliliter.

The fixed and volatile acidity level distributions both look fairly normal, but with some right-skewedness. Both these columns measure the density of different kinds of acid in the wine. Fixed acidity measures tartaric acidwhile volatile acidity measures acetic acid. High levels of acetic acid can cause a vinegar taste in the wine, as noted in the author provided data info text file.

The citric acid distribution shows an unusually high number of wines at 0 and near 0.5 g/dm^3. Overall thedistribution does not appear very normal but other than those 2 irregular peaks, it looks like the count of wines with citric acid levels from 0 to 0.5 fluctuates and then starts falling off at higher citric acid levels. There is also an outlier near 1.

The original residual sugar distribution looks long tailed so I applied a logarithmic scale transformation. The transformed distribution appears much more normal than before, but is still somewhat long-tailed.

The chlorides level is basically the density of various salts in the wine. The original distribution looked long-tailed and applying a logarithmic scale transformation the new distribution looks much more normal, with a mean value at around 0.9.

Sulfur dioxide (SO2) is a biproduct of fermentation, but most winemakers actually add significantly more of it as a preservative and anti-microbial agent. The SO2 can either be free, where it exists in equilibrium between its molecular form as well as two ionic forms in solution, or it can be bound, meaning its chemically attached to another compound in the wine. The total SO2 column is the combination of both free and bound SO2. Both SO2 distributions appear long-tailed, so I applied scale transformations to get them to look more normal.

For the Free SO2 distribution, a square root transformation worked best. There is an unusually large peak at around 5-6 but other than that the new distribution appears normal.

For the Total SO2 distribution, a logarithmic scale transformation worked better and overall it appears quite normal in the new graph, with its mean at around 46.5.

Sulfates are wine-additives that can add to the sulfur dioxide levels of the wine. The original distribution looked somewhat long-tailed and a logarithmic scale transformation makes the new graph look much more normal, with a mean of around 0.66.

The wine density distribution looks quite normal, with all of its values very close to 1, the density of water. the distribution is not centered at 1 however. Most of the wines have a density slightly less than 1, and the overall mean is 0.997.

The pH is a measure of acidity based on the concentration of hydrogen cations in a solution. The typical scale goes from 0 to 14, with a pH of 7 being the pH of water and considered neutral. Anything less than 7 is acidic, and anything more than 7 is basic.

For this dataset, the pH distribution appears normal, centered around 3.3. All of the wines are below 7.

The percent alcohol distrubtion does not look normal. It is skewed right, with a large peak around 9.5, and then the counts decrease as the percent alcohol increases. Applying square root or logarithmic scale transformations does not normalize this distribution.

Quality scores go from 0 to 10, but in this dataset, only scores from 3 to 8 actually occurred. The most common scores were 5 and 6, and the overall distribution looks normal. The mean quality score is 5.6.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset is made up of 13 columns, with 1599 observations. The first column is just the unique number given to each wine in sequence, going from 1 to 1599, so really there are only 12 variables. Of those 12 variables, 11 are measures of various chemical properties, mainly densities of particular compounds in the wine. The 12th variable is the quality score of the wine.

All 12 variables are numerical, with no real ordered factor variables. That said, the quality column can be treated like an ordered factor variable because it is an integer score that can only go from 0 to 10. And in this dataset, it only goes from 3 to 8.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of this dataset is the quality score, which goes from 0 to 10 with a higher score signifying a better rated wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Besides the quality score, the other features of the dataset are all chemical properties of the wine and may be linked to higher or lower quality wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I did not add any columns to the data. I thought about adding a column for bound sulfur dioxide, which would be the total sulfur dioxide subtracted by the free sulfur dioxide, but after investigating why sulfur dioxide levels are measured, plus the total sulfur dioxide will of course be related to the bound sulfur dioxide, I decided against it.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The dataset did contain some unusual distributions, but most were fairly normal, and some became normal after a scale transformation. Using logarithmic or square root scale transformations on any distributions that appeared long-tailed typically helped to normalize them, except for the alcohol content distribution.

Here is a correlation matrix of all columns in the dataset, excluding the first column which is just a sequential list of the entries. Looking at the main output in the quality column, the chemical property with the strongest linear relationship is the alcohol content with a correlation of 0.48. The quality score’s relationship with volatile acid is also relatively strong. And the weakest relationships are with residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, and pH.

Looking at other variables, I see density has a relatively strong positive linear relationship with fixed acidity level and an inverse linear relationship with alcohol content. Fixed acidity level also has a direct relationship with citric acid content, which makes sense as citric acid levels should directly contribute to fixed acid levels since citric acid is a fixed acid.

Alcohol content and quality score had a correlation of 0.48. The scatterplot shows that wines with scores of 8 and 7 typically have more alcohol than wines with a score of 3 or 4.

Using boxplots gives a better picture of the data. From this I see that as wine quality score goes up from 6 to 7 to 8, alcohol content also increases for the bulk of the wines. However, ignoring the many outliers present in wines with a score of 5, we can see the bulk of those wines actually had less alcohol content than for wines with a score of 4.

Again, the relationship in the scatter plot is apparent, though this time its an inverse relationship. Looking at the boxplots, wines with a score of 8 and 7 are similar, but as the wines’ score gets lower, volatile acid level increases in a pretty linear fashion.

Volatile acid level is basically the amount of acetic acid in the wine, which at high levels will cause a vinegary taste.

According to the authors of the dataset, “citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines.” Looking at citric acid content graphed against quality score, wines with scores of 7 and 8 do seem to have higher amounts of citric acid, but that pattern doesn’t really hold true for lower scores. The overall relationship is also quite weak with a correlation of 0.23.

Looking specifically at wines with a score of 7 vs wines with a score of 6, the 6 score wines are pretty evenly spread in terms of of citric acid level, but 7 score wines have a clear lack of data points around 0.2 g/dm^3 citric acid, with a grouping of outlier points that are have lower citric acid levels.

One thing I was curious about was how free sulfur dioxide levels related to some of the other variables. I looked at free sulfur versus pH as well as free sulfur vs sulfates.

Free sulfur exists in a chemical equilibrium between multiple states. It will exist as a gas, molecular sulfur dioxide, as a bisulfite ion with a negative charge, and as a sulfite ion with two negative charges, by giving up a hydrogen ion. This relationship made me wonder if free sulfur dioxide levels could have a link to pH. According to the correlation matrix there was no linear relationship but I still wanted a closer look.

Sulfates is a measure of how much sulfate preservatives were added to the wine. The authors say that these additives should add to free sulfur levels but according to the correlation matrix there was no relationship between them.

The density of the wines was moderately correlated to fixed acidity level and alcohol content. Alcohol, specifically ethanol, has a lower density than water, so a wine with higher alcohol content having a lower density makes sense. But, I wasn’t sure how fixed acidity level relates. Looking at the fixed acidity vs the density, the direct linear relationship is very noticeable.

Comparing fixed acidity to alcohol content, there’s no real pattern that I can see, and the correlation is also quite weak which leads me to believe that however fixed acidity level and density are linked, its independent from alcohol content’s effect on density.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The main feature of this dataset, the quality score, correlated most strongly with alcohol content and volatile acid level. Higher alcohol levels were associated with better quality scores and higher volatile acid levels were associated with lower quality scores. Percent alcohol having this strong an effect on quality (with a correlation of 0.48) surprised me, as I don’t think a wine needs to be very strong to be good. The quality’s relationship with volatile acidity is far less surprising as according to the authors, a high volatile acidity level means a vinegary taste.

I was also surprised by the lack of relationship between quality and citric acid level as according to the author, citric acid adds flavor and freshness to a wine. And there was no real relationship between pH and quality which also surprised me, as I thought pH could definitely effect taste. Of course there are many drinks have even lower pH’s, such as coca cola soft drinks have a pH of around 2.5.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Density had a surprisingly strong relationship with fixed acidity level, and free sulfur dioxide level had a surprisingly weak to no relationship with both pH and sulfates added.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Fixed acidity level had the strongest relationships in the dataset, with a correlation of 0.67 to citric acid level, 0.67 to density, and -0.68 to pH. Most of these relationships are not suprising. Citric acid is a type of fixed acid so of course they are related. And having a lot of fixed acid will of course lower the pH. However, as stated previously, density having a moderately strong correlation with fixed acidity level was unanticipated.

Multivariate Plots Section

Here is a depiction of free sulfur dioxide vs pH over different qualities. The distributions are all pretty similar. Wines with an 8 quality score look somewhat positively correlated but with too few points its probably not statistically significant.

Here is free sulfur vs pH over different qualities, with a color gradient representing the fixed acidity level. Higher fixed acidity levels causes a lower pH, and I wanted to see if maybe that effect was masking any effects free sulfur dioxide could have on the pH.

Darker colors are more common at higher levels of pH, which was already shown in the bivariate section looking at the relationship between fixed acidity and pH. I don’t see anything that indicated fixed acidity levels are masking free sulfur’s effect on pH, and this holds true for all qualities of wine.

I then looked at the interesting relationship between density and fixed acidity. Density is negatively associated with alcohol content because alcohol is less dense than water, but I wasn’t sure why fixed acidity had any relationship with density.

Looking at fixed acidity vs density, with a color gradient representing alcohol content, as well as looking at it over different qualities of wine, there looks to be a very strong relationship between high percent alcohol wines and fixed acidity, though they have no correlation when I looked at just fixed acidity vs alcohol in the bivariate section.

Though the most obvious relationship is between alcohol and density, most of the ligher color points are on the left side of the first graph. Looking at this split into different graphs for every quality, this effect holds true mainly only for wines with scores of 4, 5, and 6. While wines with scores of 3 and 8 had too few points to establish a pattern, wines with a quality of 7 seemed to have less of a relationship between alcohol and fixed acidity.

I also looked at sulfates vs free sulfur dioxide in the bivariate section but I wanted to try seeing if there was a pattern when I included total sulfur dioxide as well, as perhaps the sulfur additives were getting bound and would thus not be free.

Because the sulfates distribution had some far right outliers, I only used data up to the 95th percentile of the sulfates distribution so the color differences would be more even.

However, there didn’t seem to be any apparent pattern to sulfate level versus either of these variables. There is a clear positive association between free sulfur and total sulfur, which is to be expected.

I used linear regression to try and find a model to best explain the quality score output based on certain chemical properties of the wine. Looking at just alcohol as the explanatory variable there was a clear statistically significant effect on quality. With an R-squared value of 0.226, alcohol level only explains about 23% of the quality scores variance.

Adding in other variables that shared a correlation with quality, and none that were associated with each other, the R-squared value improved to about 0.334. One of the variables, citric acid level, did not have a statistically significant relationship however.

Even though density is not my main output of this dataset, I was still interested in how and why fixed acidity had a positive correlation with it. So using linear regression, fixed acidity does have a statistically significant relationship with density and by itself has an R-squared of 0.45. Combined with alcohol, which had no correlation with fixed acidity, the R-squared jumps to 0.65.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

In my investigation, though I thought free sulfur levels might have an effect on pH, I did not find any evidence of that in the bivariate section. Looking at it across different qualities, I still did not find any pattern or associations. So as far as I can tell, free sulfur did not have an effect on pH, despite how free sulfur dioxide in the form of bisulfites in solution can dissassociate further and add more hydrogen cations to solution.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Looking at fixed acidity versus density, a direct correlation became apparent in the bivariate section that I had no explanation for. Looking at it compared with percent alcohol levels, there did seem to be a hidden relationship between alcohol content and fixed acidity that only held true for certain quality scores. Higher alcohol content causes lower density which is why I thought alcohol content might also contribute to how fixed acidity relates to density.

Without further investigation I can’t say if this relationship between alcohol and fixed acidity that only occurred at certain qualities is causal or even real; it may just be statistical noise. But it may be something interesting to look into with further data.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I did create some standard linear regression models to try and fit a line that would explain how quality score varied with other chemical properties of the wine. The model did find clear statistical evidence that alcohol, volatile acidity, and sulfates had an effect on quality, but the linear model only explained about 33% of how quality varied.

I also looked at how density could be explained through fixed acidity and alcohol content.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Here is the total sulfur dioxide distribution with a logarithmic scale transformation. On a linear scale, the distribution was long-tailed, but with this logarithmic scale the distribution looks very normal, albeit with some significant variance. This tells me that most wines have a relatively low total sulfur dioxide level, yet there are then many outliers who have much higher sulfur dioxide levels compared to the bulk of the wines.

Plot Two

Description Two

In the correlation matrix I saw that alcohol content had the strongest linear relationship to the main output of the dataset, quality score. Looking at the boxplots of % alcohol separated by quality, I can see that wines with a score of 8 had a higher alcohol content than wines with a score of 7, which were higher in alcohol than wines with a score of 6, which were higher than wines with lower scores. But, interestingly, wines with a score of 3, 4, and 5 did not have very different alcohol levels, though the wines with a score of 5’s distribution did have a lot of outliers.

Plot Three

Description Three

The most interesting relationship I found was between fixed acidity and density. They had a correlation of 0.67, and a positive association is apparent looking at this graph. Alcohol content was also associated with density in an inverse relationship. That relationship was to be expected since alcohol has a lower density than water, and wine has a very close density to water. Looking at how percent alcohol could be contributing to any relationship between fixed acidity and density, I graphed all three variables together, plus split by quality score. And despite alcohol content having no correlation to fixed acidity level, it did appear that alcohol was typically lower when fixed acidity was lower for wines with a quality score of 6 and 7. Those graphs appear lighter on the right side and darker on the left side. However that’s actually the opposite of what would be true if percent alcohol was a contributor to fixed acidity’s relationship to density, since percent alcohol is negatively associated with density, I would expect it to be negatively associated with fixed acidity. This hidden relationship between percent alcohol and fixed acidity may just be statistical noise.

Reflection

Looking through this dataset, I was able to determine that alcohol content, volatile acidity, and sulfate additive level were all statistically significant contributors to quality score. Sulfates are added to wine to act as antioxidants anti-microbial agents, and their level had a positive association with quality. Volatile acidity is basically the amount of acetic acid present in the wine, which at higher levels can give the wine a vinegar taste, and had a negative association with quality. Alcohol content had a positive relationship with quality, but only up to a point, as lower scoring wines had pretty similar alcohol content distributions.

There were many suprising things I found in the dataset, such as free sulfur dioxide’s lack of a relationship with pH, alcohol’s relatively strong relationship with quality, as well as fixed acidity’s relationship with density. I struggled to find an explanation for why fixed acidity had a somewhat strong (correlation of 0.67) relationship with density. Looking at how percent alcohol could maybe contribute to it didn’t help unfortunately.

For future work I would want to look into this relationship between density and fixed acidity, and into fixed acidity in general to establish how it can affect density. Now, density in the context of this dataset, isn’t a very important as it doesn’t have much of a relationship with the main output, quality score. But I am still curious as to how fixed acidity would affect density, and finding out why could reveal interesting findings, even if they wouldn’t be very crucial to the context of this particular dataset.

Also I would probably look for additional chemical properties to test against quality score to see if maybe a better model can be found to predict quality.
